Reason: For p-diethylaminobenzaldehyde, based on the molecular structure given by the SMILES notation, we can consider the influence of its functional groups on the melting point relative to benzene. Benzene, as the basic aromatic unit, has a melting point of 5.5°C. Substituents on benzene can either increase or decrease this melting point depending on their nature and the interactions they encourage. The aldehyde group (C=O) typically increases melting point due to the possibility of hydrogen bonding and dipole-dipole interactions (+20°C). The combined effects of diethylamine (N(C2H5)2) groups are tricky; while amino groups can increase melting points through hydrogen bonding, the introduction of bulky alkyl groups (ethyl groups in this case) often decreases the melting point due to increased molecular size and steric hindrance, which disrupts the crystal lattice (-25°C per diethylamino group). Therefore, each functional group contributes as follows: aldehyde +20°C, diethylamino group -25°C x 2 for the two ethyl groups in the p-diethylamino structure.
